.SH "NAME"
find \- traverse a file tree
.PP
finddepth \- traverse a directory structure depth-first
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    use File::Find;
\&    find(\e&wanted, '/foo','/bar');
\&    sub wanted { ... }
.Ve
.Vb 3
\&    use File::Find;
\&    finddepth(\e&wanted, '/foo','/bar');
\&    sub wanted { ... }
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
The first argument to \fIfind()\fR is either a hash reference describing the
operations to be performed for each file, a code reference, or a string
that contains a subroutine name.  If it is a hash reference, then the
value for the key \f(CWwanted\fR should be a code reference.  This code
reference is called \fIthe wanted() function\fR below.
.PP
Currently the only other supported key for the above hash is
\f(CWbydepth\fR, in presense of which the walk over directories is
performed depth-first.  Entry point \fIfinddepth()\fR is a shortcut for
specifying \f(CW{ bydepth =\fR 1}> in the first argument of \fIfind()\fR.
.PP
The \fIwanted()\fR function does whatever verifications you want.
\f(CW$File::Find::dir\fR contains the current directory name, and \f(CW$_\fR the
current filename within that directory.  \f(CW$File::Find::name\fR contains
\f(CW"$File::Find::dir/$_"\fR.  You are \fIchdir()\fR'd to \f(CW$File::Find::dir\fR when
the function is called.  The function may set \f(CW$File::Find::prune\fR to
prune the tree.
.PP
File::Find assumes that you don't alter the \f(CW$_\fR variable.  If you do then
make sure you return it to its original value before exiting your function.
.PP
This library is useful for the \f(CWfind2perl\fR tool, which when fed,
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    find2perl / -name .nfs\e* -mtime +7 \e
\&        -exec rm -f {} \e; -o -fstype nfs -prune
.Ve
produces something like:
.PP
.Vb 10
\&    sub wanted {
\&        /^\e.nfs.*$/ &&
\&        (($dev,$ino,$mode,$nlink,$uid,$gid) = lstat($_)) &&
\&        int(-M _) > 7 &&
\&        unlink($_)
\&        ||
\&        ($nlink || (($dev,$ino,$mode,$nlink,$uid,$gid) = lstat($_))) &&
\&        $dev < 0 &&
\&        ($File::Find::prune = 1);
\&    }
.Ve
Set the variable \f(CW$File::Find::dont_use_nlink\fR if you're using AFS,
since AFS cheats.
.PP
\f(CWfinddepth\fR is just like \f(CWfind\fR, except that it does a depth-first
search.
.PP
Here's another interesting wanted function.  It will find all symlinks
that don't resolve:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    sub wanted {
\&        -l && !-e && print "bogus link: $File::Find::name\en";
\&    }
.Ve
.SH "BUGS"
There is no way to make find or finddepth follow symlinks.

